<p><strong><em>American English and Dialectology, Select
Bibliography</em></strong> (rev. 3/99)</p>

<p><u>General works for the non-specialist audience</u></p>

<p>American English is a fascinating subject that, as with many
things, can be appreciated at many levels. For those who are not
interested in college-level academic studies, a widely available
resource is the article on American English in the Microsoft
Encarta computer encyclopedia (Encarta 99 and following). Two books
from the 1950s, Marckwardt's <em>American English</em> and Pyles'
<em>Words and Ways of American English</em>, remain very readable
for a general audience, although they do not contain information
about recent change in American English. Another classic work for
the general audience is Mencken's <em>The American Language</em>,
which is best appreciated in its one-volume abridged edition
(1963). Two dictionaries that treat American English specifically
are Mathews' <em>Dictionary of Americanisms</em> (1951) and
Cassidy's <em>Dictionary of American Regional English</em> (now
complete through the third volume). A readable short volume which
treats the importance of American dialects in primary and secondary
education is Wolfram and Christian's <em>Dialects and
Education</em> (1989). Among periodicals, <em>English Today</em> is
readable by a general audience, as are most articles in <em>
American Speech</em>. The latter is published by the American
Dialect Society, to which many non-academics belong as well as the
usual crowd of professors, students, lexicographers, and others
centrally interested in language studies.</p>

<p>Adventurous souls may wish to graduate from books for the
general audience to the more academic treatments below. Some of
these volumes are pretty technical, but many others will be quite
accessible for those who have spent a little time becoming familiar
with the subject by reading one or more of the titles mentioned
above.</p>

